My googling skills seem to be coming up short on the following topic - anyone know about this? 

Why does California pay other states to take our excess electricity when we generate too much (e.g. midday from solar)? Why can't we find some other way to use it / get rid of it?

Thanks! I still don't see the answer to the question of why we don't do something else with the excess electricity, e.g. "burn it" in some way? is there no other end point besides sending it to other states?
Makes sense, thanks. It doesn't seem like there is much appetite for building an off-ramp for excess electricity. Paying others to take it is = easiest route.
Of course there are solutions upstream that should be looked at, e.g. stopping generation sooner, long-term contracts, subsidy incentives

Sad day for nuclear in Germany, though the German people have started to change their mind on nuclear, with more in favor of nuclear (60%) than ever before. 

An interesting overview here: https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/A-guide-The-end-of-Germany%E2%80%99s-nuclear-power?feed=feed

The IPCC (the UN's climate change panel) is a good source on this: https://archive.ipcc.ch/publications_and_data/ar4/wg3/en/ch4s4-3-2-4.html

"Even if the nuclear industry expands significantly, sufficient fuel is available for centuries."

We'll get better at extracting/refining/recycling (which we don't do in the US!) just like we have with oil. "Peak oil" was something we kept thought was coming for us, but have found ways to economically extract more. I believe the same curve will happen with uranium, and PLENTY of time until any chance of running out

An excellent post on nuclear waste: 

https://jackdevanney.substack.com/p/600-year-old-spent-nuclear-fuel-is?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&nthPub=70

"For practical purposes, spent nuclear fuel remains radioactive forever. However, the penetrating form of radiation is essentially gone in 600 years. After that, the used fuel must be swallowed to be harmful. But that would require eating rocks."

I'm excited to officially announce Antares! 

I started Antares with my co-founder Jordan Bramble to achieve our shared vision of abundant clean energy for all, from Earth to the asteroid belt. 

https://www.antaresindustries.com/

We are building micro-sized nuclear reactors that can be mass-manufactured to provide power to remote and austere off-grid locations worldwide. We’re starting with the defense market to enable our military and allies to untether from the burden of fossil fuel supply chains and power next-generation defense tech.

We've raised $8M in seed funding and are based in LA! 

If you’re excited about bringing small-scale nuclear to the world, get in touch!
